Wednesday has not reached an agreement on the future status of the province, during the last session of negotiations to Vienna.
In the end, the failure.
The Serbs and the Albanians of Kosovo have ended on Wednesday morning at Ford, in Austria, a sixth and last session of discussions without having been able to overcome their differences on the future statute of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to come to an agreement on the Statute," the European mediator Wolfgang ischinger declared, at a press conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region was at stake, its American counterpart, frank wisner, exhorted to Belgrade and Pristina to respect their determination in preserving peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"We do not anticipate violence by now but we enter into a very difficult period," he added, pointing out that "clear tensions exist."
The aim of the mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which regroups the European Union, the United States and Russia, Iran, one last time on Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province populated to 90% of Albanians might become more clear when ischinger, wisner and the Russian mediator Alexander botsane-khartchenko will return to its relation to the Security Council of the United Nations, up to 10 December.
The discussions of Ford, next to Vienna, constituted the sixth session and last of negotiations from the troika has been entrusted to a new mediation by the UN, the last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that its mediation will be finished on 10 December.
The Russians, who already have blocked in the Security Council the concession of independence in Kosovo, they insist on a pursuit of negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution", said botsane-khartchenko.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of administration of the UN in Kosovo, the Western consider that independence under the supervision of the European Union is the only viable solution.
Pristina is prepared to proclaim unilaterally if the Security Council does not resolve on its behalf.
Belgrade insists on autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been found, announced the President of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the hotel of Ford where it is celebrated since Monday these" negotiations of the last opportunity ".
Hashim Thaci, former Commander of the rebellion of Kosovo and the future Prime Minister of the province, has given a part of their grief.
But added that the plan of autonomy presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to murders and deportations."
"domino effect"
The Serbian President Boris Tadic considerato for his part that a compromise was always feasible, recognizing the Albanian majority in Kosovo, against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade says particularly fear a domino effect "in a region still weakened by the war of independence of the 1990s.
"for Serbia, said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted so that every decision belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its ally, Russia has a right of veto.
"the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word"
Only a solution in the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia, had declared the Serbian Prime Minister, Vojislav Kostunica.
"these negotiations have lasted two years.
They must run as they have begun: in the Security Council. "
The journalists, Fatmir sedjiu had answered that "the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the Statute, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence on the part of the Albanians would" in coordination with the West.
