Those who are in power are not too bad, why replace? "
A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidential character, the Nazi files of bad arolsen, which describes the fates of 17.5 million victims of the regime, are in free access.
The 47 million documents of files, stored on 27 km from shelves to bad arolsen (Hesse), were not so far to be consulted only in an end "humanitarian", that is to say of an individual and nominative, at the request of a former victim or of their rightful claimants.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States came to an agreement in May 2006 to open to the search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of the agreement by all the States has ended, the gap is effective from yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to bad arolsen will make searches "particularly on the displacement of the prisonieros, the population of the fields and the state of health of the workers forced, explains challenge, the director of these files administered by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed to the opening to the public of these documents nominative, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or handicap mental of certain victims of the deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the orders of halting established by the Gestapo had been assembled after war in a practical aim: to find the compatriots deported or submitted in the obligatory work and, possibly, to contribute a test of its internment, with the aim of opening the way to their compensation.
Still today in bad arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees treat tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to bad arolsen has a limited interest.
"there is nothing fundamentally new that there is hope of these documents, had declared in 2006 Professor Wolfgang Benz, the director of the centre on anti-Semitism in Technische universität of Berlin.
