New fears on the gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute for the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia, increases the risk that affect the export of fuel to Western Europe on the part of Russia.
The majority of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, by which each close contact between the two nations, is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher rates of transit.
A dispute this last year, reduce the provisions to the States of the EU.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian Government and the Russian State, the owner of the gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money that should pay Ukraine by the Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom declared that it will receive more to Ukraine, since this has committed itself to pay 50% extra in 2008 for gas that comes from the one Turkmenistan.
The analysts say that it could be that Ukraine pays a 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important traffic for the gas during the talks," said the Minister of Economics Anatoly kinakh to Reuters news agency.
"the changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments on the levels of the rates of traffic [towards Western Europe] via Ukraine.
The last great for the gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut the supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which rose rapidly prices.
The Russian gas represents the fourth part of the supply of the EU.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but most of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own with gas supply of Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations of Central Asia.
