The climate of Venus can give an idea of the future of the earth
Venus could have been a time an appropriate place for life, declared scientific yesterday.
The data of a European spaceship in orbit showed the world more resemblance to a of the land of what had previously been observed.
Venus is the planet more closely to the land.
The two planets have similar size and occupy similar Venus, although it is slightly nearer to the sun.
Millions of years, Venus could have had similar conditions to which made of the land a habitable planet, the scientists believe now.
But the effects of carbon dioxide, and the greenhouse effect, the atmospheric erosion by the solar radiation and the slower solar rotation sent Venus at a very different kind of development.
Today, the world has not water, the temperature of the surface is sufficient to lead and it is being eroded by the winds and storms rays.
The results of the European Space Agency for the Venus express, who has studied the planet for a year, offers a picture of how the land could develop disastrous changes because of the climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, the department of physics of the Oxford University and one of the leaders of the mission Venus express, states: "It is clarified cause climate in Venus is so different from that of the land, when they are so similar planets.
"our new information make it possible to build a scenario in which Venus began as the land, possibly with an inhabitable millions of years."
