Buses bring the refugees back to work - and the fight against Al-Qaeda
The first buses with Iraqi refugees of Syria started to come to Baghdad yesterday, expelling the ones that remained without effective, without extensions of the visa and who hoped that the city to return to normality.
Some even had returned to fight against the militants who drove them out of their homes.
In the season of buses of mansour, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official convoy of government consisted of a dozen or so of buses, the terminal was full of refugees from Syria and Jordan, which had returned in private transport.
"I decided to go to Syria that they killed many doctors in Baghdad," says Sabah al-qubaisi, doctor.
"I returned today by what I saw in the TV and what I have read in the newspapers, on what happened in Baghdad, and that is surely now".
"say that the army of mahdi left of killing people", it declares, referring to the Shi'ite militia of religious militant cleric moqtada al-sadr, who arranged its troops a momentary cease.
Qassim to the atwani, Shiite 38 years and teacher in the area of amariyah, returned to his two children because it was impossible to renew their visa in Syria, since the regime does not want the Iraqis working in his country.
Their Shiite in amariyah called by telephone, to say that an ally of the United States has helped to remove Al-Qaeda outside its bastion the west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers of Jordan was the leader of a tribe Shiite and who had been driven from his home in sleikh in the north of Baghdad, for an attack of grenades, after which urged the citizens to get up against Al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
"two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that it had begun a militia anti in sleikh and that it needed my support and that of my colleagues.
For that reason I have returned today, declared sabaah obeidi, 62.
Many said to be swayed by the growing calm in the capital from the troops of the groups of "citizens concerned", armed and working in cooperation with the soldiers of the USA to defend their local communities.
But many people declared to be returned by the refusal of visas and the lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis were established in the last few years.
Salaam al-samarrai, 51 years and father of three children, gave voice to the common suspicion among the ones, that nouri, Prime Minister, asked the Syrian Government to impose restrictions on visas for refugees to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people believe have fled the country because of the sectarian bands of death.
"We were well until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to the Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq," said the Sunni.
"I cannot believe in a government which supports the criminals who to my home after that left".
Part of the reason of the cessation of violence is that the Sunnis, have been expelled from the areas and vice versa, relaxing the tension.
There is the fear that a sudden wave of refugees does arise again the sectarian tensions and starts the fight.
The small Sarre, good education.
The smallest federal state is the first in the vocational training and even shines through the international orientation of its high schools.
As in any country, the sarlandeses only lack an educational field.
"I explained yesterday by the fiftieth time to not sarlandés that we are not franseses" - this was the motorcycle ironic on themselves of the smallest federal State for its cencuentenario.
At the same time, France and Luxembourg have a greater role in the educational system of Sarre that in a study of the Institute of the German economy (iw) called "bildungsmonitor" occupied the fifth place.
In this way, the high schools by tradition have good relations with those countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was melted in 1948 by thefranseses.
Up to now the students can finish their university career with two or three dipolmas.
As a consequence, for the procentaje foreign students is high, of 15, 6 by hundreds.
However, the number of students originating from the Sarre is higher than the average in the high schools; many of them do not have a bacillerato.
"in the Sarre use is made of the system of the professional education", says plünnecke, experte of educational sector in the Institute of the German economy (iw).
More than five young people for their degree in the vocational school; well, it turns out that the Sarre is 7 points% above the national average.
On the contrary, the variety of the range of possibilities for an education is very wide.
The offer of the double races, in relation to the number of population, is the second best in Germany.
In spite of the practical vocational training and a growing demand, the number of science graduates of engineering fell to a third in recent years.
That was the reason why the Ministry of Education of Sarre obliged the high schools to do more publicity for the specialities in science engineering.
"after the first study of steps, we made some reforms in the schools of general education," States a spokesman of the Ministry of Education.
So the Government introduced comparative tests throughout the country.
So that the children start as soon as possible to study the last year of the project called "kita-jahr, this does not have any cost; in the meantime, this model also imitates the other federal.
The comparison with the next studies will show whether it has increased the performance of the students.
According to the report steps of the year 2003, the number of students backward developing student desminuyó of 29 to 20%.
But, in general, the Sarre does not improve very much like other federal states.
In Bavaria, the pupils can calculate better.
For disappointment of the sarlandeses, the report steps does not compare the knowledge of foreign languages, although in this field could achieve good results.
In spite of the fact that the sarlandeses are not French, the language of the neighbours is an obligatory subject in the secondary schools.
